<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Slip Nip" class="currentChild" href="Slip_Nip">Slip Nip</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In an offset press's <a title="Continuous-Flow Dampening System" href="Continuous-Flow_Dampening_System">continuous-flow dampening system</a>, the line of contact between two rollers rotating in opposite directions, typically a hard <a title="Transfer Roller" href="Transfer_Roller">transfer roller</a> and a <a title="Form Roller" href="Form_Roller">form roller</a>, either belonging to the <a title="Dampening System" href="Dampening_System">dampening system</a>, or shared by the dampening and inking systems. The nip between two rollers rotating in the same direction is called a <a title="Reverse Slip Nip" href="Reverse_Slip_Nip">reverse slip nip</a>, occasionally produced on presses as a means of preventing the excess <a title="Fountain Solution" href="Fountain_Solution">fountain solution</a> returning from the plate from interacting with the "fresh" fountain solution coming from the fountain. (See <a title="Dampening System" href="Dampening_System">Dampening System</a> and <a title="Reverse Slip Nip" href="Reverse_Slip_Nip">Reverse Slip Nip</a>.) 
</p>
